Bayesian Model Examples

4 Turnout: logit/probit models for binary data

library("tidyverse")
library("rstanarm")
library("rstan")

Voter turnout is coded as a binary indicator (y=1 if voted, 0 otherwise) and related to covariates via a logit model. The data comprise a random 3,000 observation subset of a much larger data set analyzed by Jonathan Nagler (Nagler 1994):

\[ \begin{aligned}[t] y_i &\sim \mathsf{Bernoulli}(\pi_i) \\ \pi_i &= \frac{1}{1 + e^{-\eta_i}} \\ \eta_i &= \alpha + x_i \beta \end{aligned} \] The regression parameters are given weakly informative priors on the logit scale, \[ \begin{aligned}[t] \alpha &\sim \mathsf{Normal}(0, 10)\\ \beta_k &\sim \mathsf{Normal}(0, 2.5) \end{aligned} \] and on the probit scale, \[ \begin{aligned}[t] \alpha &\sim \mathsf{Normal}(0, 8) \\ \beta_k &\sim \mathsf{Normal}(0, 2) \end{aligned} \]

turnout2005_mod_logit <- stan_model("stan/logit.stan")
  data {
  // response
  int N;
  int y[N];
  // covariates
  int K;
  matrix[N, K] X;
  // priors
  real alpha_mean;
  real alpha_scale;
  vector[K] beta_mean;
  vector[K] beta_scale;
}
parameters {
  real alpha;
  vector[K] beta;
}
transformed parameters {
  // linear predictor
  vector[N] eta;
  eta = alpha + X * beta;
}
model {
  alpha ~ normal(alpha_mean, alpha_scale);
  beta ~ normal(beta_mean, beta_scale);
  // y ~ bernoulli(inv_logit(eta));
  // this is faster and more numerically stable
  y ~ bernoulli_logit(eta);
}
generated quantities {
  // log-likelihood of each obs
  vector[N] log_lik;
  // probability
  vector[N] mu;
  for (i in 1:N) {
    mu[i] = inv_logit(eta[i]);
    log_lik[i] = bernoulli_logit_lpmf(y[i] | eta[i]);
  }
}

load("data/turnout2005.rda")
turnout2005_data <- within(list(), {
  N <- nrow(turnout2005)
  X <- scale(model.matrix(~ 0 + closing * poly(educ, 2) + poly(age, 2) + 
                          south + govelec, data = turnout2005))
  K <- ncol(X)
  y <- turnout2005$y
  alpha_mean <- 0
  alpha_scale <- 10
  beta_mean <- rep(0, K)
  beta_scale <- rep(2.5, K)
})

The only difference between and logit model and

turnout2005_mod_probit <- stan_model("stan/probit.stan")
  data {
  // response
  int N;
  int y[N];
  // covariates
  int K;
  matrix[N, K] X;
  // priors
  real alpha_mean;
  real alpha_scale;
  vector[K] beta_mean;
  vector[K] beta_scale;
}
parameters {
  real alpha;
  vector[K] beta;
}
transformed parameters {
  // linear predictor
  vector[N] eta;
  vector[N] mu;
  eta = alpha + X * beta;
  // mu = Phi(eta);
  // Phi_approx is faster
  mu = Phi_approx(eta);
}
model {
  alpha ~ normal(alpha_mean, alpha_scale);
  beta ~ normal(beta_mean, beta_scale);
  y ~ bernoulli(mu);
}
generated quantities {
  // log-likelihood of each obs
  vector[N] log_lik;
  for (i in 1:N) {
    log_lik[i] = bernoulli_lpmf(y[i] | mu[i]);
  }
}

turnout2005_fit_logit <- sampling(turnout2005_mod_logit, data = turnout2005_data)
turnout2005_fit_logit

These models can also be estimated with the rstanarm function rstanarm:

turnout2005_fit_logit2 <- 
  stan_glm(y ~ closing * poly(educ, 2) + poly(age, 2) + south + govelec,
         family = binomial(),
         data = turnout2005)
turnout2005_fit_logit2

For the probit model, the priors need to be reduced.

turnout2005_fit_probit2 <-
  stan_glm(y ~ closing * poly(educ, 2) + poly(age, 2) + south + govelec,
         family = binomial(link = "probit"),
         prior_intercept = normal(location = 0, scale = 8, autoscale = TRUE),
         prior = normal(location = 0, scale = 1.5, autoscale = TRUE),
         data = turnout2005)
turnout2005_fit_probit2
#> stan_glm
#>  family:  binomial [probit]
#>  formula: y ~ closing * poly(educ, 2) + poly(age, 2) + south + govelec

Questions

  1. Is there any difference in the fit of the probit and logit?
  2. How do these fits compare to using a generalized logit model?
